'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "This started with enhancing tags, but when I was done I discovered a
sigsev which could be triggered even from Rust code. I knew I had
screwed up the lifetimes and unsafe code.

So, I started working and I kept unravelling more and more.

Slice and vec have been split into their own files as lib.rs was
getting large.

Many From traits were changed to work with &T instead of T because of
lifetime issues.

In this PR, some C FFI APIs for tags have been removed. A subsequent PR
will add them back and enhance them. I wanted to keep the PR size to be
somewhat manageable.

Some places using some form of string have changed to use
`Cow<'static, str>`. This allows you to borrow static strings, and own
all others. When calling from C, the difference is very little because
they _should_ have been copied (probably, was unsafe if not). I believe
these are the changes which actually fixed the crash.", 'created_at': '2022-04-01T23:54:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-04T08:52:34Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': 'body': "This started with enhancing tags, but when I was done I discovered a
sigsev which could be triggered even from Rust code. I knew I had
screwed up the lifetimes and unsafe code.

So, I started working and I kept unravelling more and more.

Slice and vec have been split into their own files as lib.rs was
getting large.

Many From traits were changed to work with &T instead of T because of
lifetime issues.

In this PR, some C FFI APIs for tags have been removed. A subsequent PR
will add them back and enhance them. I wanted to keep the PR size to be
somewhat manageable.

Some places using some form of string have changed to use
`Cow<'static, str>`. This allows you to borrow static strings, and own
all others. When calling from C, the difference is very little because
they _should_ have been copied (probably, was unsafe if not). I believe
these are the changes which actually fixed the crash.", 'created_at': '2022-04-01T23:54:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-04T08:52:34Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': a
sigsev which could be triggered even from Rust code. I knew I had
screwed up the lifetimes and unsafe code.

So, I started working and I kept unravelling more and more.

Slice and vec have been split into their own files as lib.rs was
getting large.

Many From traits were changed to work with &T instead of T because of
lifetime issues.

In this PR, some C FFI APIs for tags have been removed. A subsequent PR
will add them back and enhance them. I wanted to keep the PR size to be
somewhat manageable.

Some places using some form of string have changed to use
`Cow<'static, str>`. This allows you to borrow static strings, and own
all others. When calling from C, the difference is very little because
they _should_ have been copied (probably, was unsafe if not). I believe
these are the changes which actually fixed the crash.", 'created_at': '2022-04-01T23:54:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-04T08:52:34Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': sigsev which could be triggered even from Rust code. I knew I had
screwed up the lifetimes and unsafe code.

So, I started working and I kept unravelling more and more.

Slice and vec have been split into their own files as lib.rs was
getting large.

Many From traits were changed to work with &T instead of T because of
lifetime issues.

In this PR, some C FFI APIs for tags have been removed. A subsequent PR
will add them back and enhance them. I wanted to keep the PR size to be
somewhat manageable.

Some places using some form of string have changed to use
`Cow<'static, str>`. This allows you to borrow static strings, and own
all others. When calling from C, the difference is very little because
they _should_ have been copied (probably, was unsafe if not). I believe

  the gem with no binaries, so `Libddprof.binaries?` was removed.

* Use the new `DDPROF_FFI_CHARSLICE_C` to replace
  `byte_slice_from_literal`

* Introduce `char_slice_from_ruby_string` and update APIs that
  now take a char slice in 0.5.0

```ruby
puts RUBY_DESCRIPTION

utf8 = ''.encode(::Encoding::UTF_8).freeze
puts utf8.encoding

ENV['FOO'] = ''

puts utf8.encoding
```

When executed in the `jruby:9.3.4.0-jre11` docker image with `LANG=en_US.UTF-8`, e.g.:

US-ASCII
```

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c
ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_new(void);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_push(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec, ddprof_ffi_Tag tag);
ddprof_ffi_Slice_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_as_slice(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_drop(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_parse(ddprof_ffi_CharSlice string);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_clone(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
```", 'created_at': '2022-03-29T21:44:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-31T09:32:16Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': '0ad78dc1d5e35679343470ea51e503783894684e', 'assignee': 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c
ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_new(void);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_push(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec, ddprof_ffi_Tag tag);
ddprof_ffi_Slice_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_as_slice(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_drop(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_parse(ddprof_ffi_CharSlice string);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_clone(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
```", 'created_at': '2022-03-29T21:44:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-31T09:32:16Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': '0ad78dc1d5e35679343470ea51e503783894684e', 'assignee': 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c
ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_new(void);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_push(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec, ddprof_ffi_Tag tag);
ddprof_ffi_Slice_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_as_slice(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_drop(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_parse(ddprof_ffi_CharSlice string);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_clone(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
```", 'created_at': '2022-03-29T21:44:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-30T15:19:10Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': '813954cc2fde7c7dc906e196a7b8f4f8a9bebe45', 'assignee': 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c
ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_new(void);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_push(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec, ddprof_ffi_Tag tag);
ddprof_ffi_Slice_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_as_slice(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_drop(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_parse(ddprof_ffi_CharSlice string);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_clone(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
```", 'created_at': '2022-03-29T21:44:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-30T15:18:29Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': '813954cc2fde7c7dc906e196a7b8f4f8a9bebe45', 'assignee': 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c
ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_new(void);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_push(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec, ddprof_ffi_Tag tag);
ddprof_ffi_Slice_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_as_slice(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_drop(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_parse(ddprof_ffi_CharSlice string);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_clone(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
```", 'created_at': '2022-03-29T21:44:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-30T15:07:05Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': 'ab5aa5d7a8c7aa3233a64453441d8c5ee4b5aa1b', 'assignee': 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c
ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_new(void);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_push(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec, ddprof_ffi_Tag tag);
ddprof_ffi_Slice_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_as_slice(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_drop(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_parse(ddprof_ffi_CharSlice string);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_clone(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
```", 'created_at': '2022-03-29T21:44:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-30T14:59:43Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': 'ab5aa5d7a8c7aa3233a64453441d8c5ee4b5aa1b', 'assignee': 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c
ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_new(void);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_push(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec, ddprof_ffi_Tag tag);
ddprof_ffi_Slice_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_as_slice(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_drop(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_parse(ddprof_ffi_CharSlice string);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_clone(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
```", 'created_at': '2022-03-29T21:44:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-30T14:59:15Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': 'ab5aa5d7a8c7aa3233a64453441d8c5ee4b5aa1b', 'assignee': 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Changes:

- `ddprof_ffi_Profile_serialize` returns `ddprof_ffi_SerializeResult`

Adds:

- `ddprof_ffi_SerializeResult_drop`
- `ddprof_ffi_Vec_u8_as_slice`

Removes `ddprof_ffi_EncodedProfile_delete`.

Cleans up exporter example. With the newer APIs, fewer helpers are
needed.

# Motivation

Ivo wrote a doc for API changes he wants and I had a moment and was
already In The Groove. These changes make it easier for the caller to
choose what to do with errors, and make it easier to convert the
EncodeProfile's buffer field into a slice.

# Additional Notes

I like working with Ivo.

# How to test the change?

Observe that existing code breaks, adjust code paths around the above
changes, and be on your way. I fixed up the exporter example so you can
refer to that too.

'body': "# What does this PR do?

Changes:

- `ddprof_ffi_Profile_serialize` returns `ddprof_ffi_SerializeResult`

Adds:

- `ddprof_ffi_SerializeResult_drop`
- `ddprof_ffi_Vec_u8_as_slice`

Removes `ddprof_ffi_EncodedProfile_delete`.

Cleans up exporter example. With the newer APIs, fewer helpers are
needed.

# Motivation

Ivo wrote a doc for API changes he wants and I had a moment and was
already In The Groove. These changes make it easier for the caller to
choose what to do with errors, and make it easier to convert the
EncodeProfile's buffer field into a slice.

# Additional Notes

I like working with Ivo.

# How to test the change?

Observe that existing code breaks, adjust code paths around the above
changes, and be on your way. I fixed up the exporter example so you can
refer to that too.

'body': "# What does this PR do?

Changes:

- `ddprof_ffi_Profile_serialize` returns `ddprof_ffi_SerializeResult`

Adds:

- `ddprof_ffi_SerializeResult_drop`
- `ddprof_ffi_Vec_u8_as_slice`

Removes `ddprof_ffi_EncodedProfile_delete`.

Cleans up exporter example. With the newer APIs, fewer helpers are
needed.

# Motivation

Ivo wrote a doc for API changes he wants and I had a moment and was
already In The Groove. These changes make it easier for the caller to
choose what to do with errors, and make it easier to convert the
EncodeProfile's buffer field into a slice.

# Additional Notes

I like working with Ivo.

# How to test the change?

Observe that existing code breaks, adjust code paths around the above
changes, and be on your way. I fixed up the exporter example so you can
refer to that too.

Changes:

- `ddprof_ffi_Profile_serialize` returns `ddprof_ffi_SerializeResult`

Adds:

- `ddprof_ffi_SerializeResult_drop`
- `ddprof_ffi_Vec_u8_as_slice`

Removes `ddprof_ffi_EncodedProfile_delete`.

Cleans up exporter example. With the newer APIs, fewer helpers are
needed.

# Motivation

Ivo wrote a doc for API changes he wants and I had a moment and was
already In The Groove. These changes make it easier for the caller to
choose what to do with errors, and make it easier to convert the
EncodeProfile's buffer field into a slice.

# Additional Notes

I like working with Ivo.

# How to test the change?

Observe that existing code breaks, adjust code paths around the above
changes, and be on your way. I fixed up the exporter example so you can
refer to that too.

Changes:

- `ddprof_ffi_Profile_serialize` returns `ddprof_ffi_SerializeResult`

Adds:

- `ddprof_ffi_SerializeResult_drop`
- `ddprof_ffi_Vec_u8_as_slice`

Removes `ddprof_ffi_EncodedProfile_delete`.

Cleans up exporter example. With the newer APIs, fewer helpers are
needed.

# Motivation

Ivo wrote a doc for API changes he wants and I had a moment and was
already In The Groove. These changes make it easier for the caller to
choose what to do with errors, and make it easier to convert the
EncodeProfile's buffer field into a slice.

# Additional Notes

I like working with Ivo.

# How to test the change?

Observe that existing code breaks, adjust code paths around the above
changes, and be on your way. I fixed up the exporter example so you can
refer to that too.

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c
ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_new(void);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_push(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec, ddprof_ffi_Tag tag);
ddprof_ffi_Slice_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_as_slice(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_drop(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_parse(ddprof_ffi_CharSlice string);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_clone(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
```", 'created_at': '2022-03-29T21:44:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-30T10:49:53Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': '88e92e96e3f882cb65711957e05399c9215c651e', 'assignee': 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c
ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_new(void);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_push(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec, ddprof_ffi_Tag tag);
ddprof_ffi_Slice_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_as_slice(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_drop(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag vec);

* `_delete` => `ddprof_ffi_ProfileExporterV3_delete`
* `_dtor` => `ddprof_ffi_NewProfileExporterV3Result_dtor`
* `_free` => `ddprof_ffi_Profile_free`

'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c
ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_new(void);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_push(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec, ddprof_ffi_Tag tag);
ddprof_ffi_Slice_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_as_slice(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_drop(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_parse(ddprof_ffi_CharSlice string);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_clone(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
```", 'created_at': '2022-03-29T21:44:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-30T08:55:01Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': '88e92e96e3f882cb65711957e05399c9215c651e', 'assignee': 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c
ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_new(void);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_push(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec, ddprof_ffi_Tag tag);
ddprof_ffi_Slice_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_as_slice(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_drop(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_parse(ddprof_ffi_CharSlice string);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_clone(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
```", 'created_at': '2022-03-29T21:44:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-30T08:55:01Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': '88e92e96e3f882cb65711957e05399c9215c651e', 'assignee': 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Adds:

- A new `repr(C)` `Vec` type.
- FFI functions to deal with `Vec<Tag>`, including a helper for parsing
`DD_TAGS`.
- `ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` destructor.

Removes:

- Buffer. Use `Vec<u8>` instead.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_reset`. Probably you should use
`ddprof_ffi_SendResult_drop` instead, as resetting the buffer was only
really used in the failure case of a SendResult.
- `ddprof_ffi_Buffer_free`. There aren't any APIs left which create a
`Box<Vec<u8>>` to use it on.

# Motivation

I wanted an API in PHP for dynamic tag management, and Ivo said he'd
like it for Ruby as well. 

# Additional Notes

I started off using opaque types, but cbindgen was failing to generate
correct C code for `Box<Vec<Tag>>` when used in an enum. So, instead I
made the FFI vec type. This technically saves an allocation as well.

# How to test the change?

Make the above changes, then use as normal. The functions below may be
helpful creating a dynamic array of tags:

```c
ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_new(void);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_push(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec, ddprof_ffi_Tag tag);
ddprof_ffi_Slice_tag ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_as_slice(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_drop(ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_parse(ddprof_ffi_CharSlice string);
ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag_clone(const ddprof_ffi_Vec_tag *vec);
void ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult_drop(ddprof_ffi_VecTagResult result);
```", 'created_at': '2022-03-29T21:44:02Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-30T08:55:01Z', 'closed_at': None, 'merged_at': None, 'merge_commit_sha': '88e92e96e3f882cb65711957e05399c9215c651e', 'assignee': This PR prepares the 0.5.0 Ruby packages, and includes a bunch of changes to take advantage of 0.5 improvements:

* Exclude debug information from Ruby packages
* Package Linux arm64 releases for Ruby
* Changes the strategy for the fallback package with no platform (see more details in the change to the `Rakefile`)

(I've broken it into separate commits which hopefully will make sense individually)

# Motivation

Release latest improvements for usage by the Ruby profiler.

# Additional Notes

Using `docker-compose run push_to_rubygems` to release the packages won't work until we actually upload the 0.5.0-rc.1 binaries as 0.5.0. I built the packages locally and validated the dd-trace-rb tests are green (see "How to test the change?" below).

Also note that libddprof is not yet being used in any released version of dd-trace-rb, and more validation will be done on the Ruby side before we do so.

# How to test the change?

Libddprof integration is still in PR for dd-trace-rb. Testing can be done with https://github.com/DataDog/dd-trace-rb/pull/1936 . I've built the packages locally without releasing them, and validated that libddprof integration tests in the mentioned PR are all passing. use that file. (My testing did not flag this because my initial plan
was to change `ddprof_ffi.pc` directly to add the rpath flags, and
the rename came late in the branch.)

I will include a matching change on the dd-trace-rb side.

* Package libddprof 0.5.0.rc1, including arm64 (aarch64) binaries

* Exclude libddprof debug info from packaged gems

* Simplify files_for helper

* Actually push built arm64 gem

* Change fallback package with no platform to contain all binaries

See comment in `Rakefile` for details on this decision.

'https://github.com/DataDog/libddprof/pull/39.diff', 'patch_url': 'https://github.com/DataDog/libddprof/pull/39.patch', 'merged_at': None}, 'body': '# What does this PR do?

This PR prepares the 0.5.0 Ruby packages, and includes a bunch of changes to take advantage of 0.5 improvements:

* Exclude debug information from Ruby packages
* Package Linux arm64 releases for Ruby
* Changes the strategy for the fallback package with no platform (see more details in the change to the `Rakefile`)

(I've broken it into separate commits which hopefully will make sense individually)

# Motivation

Release latest improvements for usage by the Ruby profiler.

# Additional Notes

Using `docker-compose run push_to_rubygems` to release the packages won't work until we actually upload the 0.5.0-rc.1 binaries as 0.5.0. I built the packages locally and validated the dd-trace-rb tests are green (see "How to test the change?" below).

Also note that libddprof is not yet being used in any released version of dd-trace-rb, and more validation will be done on the Ruby side before we do so.

# How to test the change?

Libddprof integration is still in PR for dd-trace-rb. Testing can be done with https://github.com/DataDog/dd-trace-rb/pull/1936 . I've built the packages locally without releasing them, and validated that libddprof integration tests in the mentioned PR are all passing. 'https://api.github.com/users/ivoanjo/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '# What does this PR do?

This PR prepares the 0.5.0 Ruby packages, and includes a bunch of changes to take advantage of 0.5 improvements:

* Exclude debug information from Ruby packages
* Package Linux arm64 releases for Ruby
* Changes the strategy for the fallback package with no platform (see more details in the change to the `Rakefile`)

(I've broken it into separate commits which hopefully will make sense individually)

# Motivation

Release latest improvements for usage by the Ruby profiler.

# Additional Notes

Using `docker-compose run push_to_rubygems` to release the packages won't work until we actually upload the 0.5.0-rc.1 binaries as 0.5.0. I built the packages locally and validated the dd-trace-rb tests are green (see "How to test the change?" below).

Also note that libddprof is not yet being used in any released version of dd-trace-rb, and more validation will be done on the Ruby side before we do so.

# How to test the change?

Libddprof integration is still in PR for dd-trace-rb. Testing can be done with https://github.com/DataDog/dd-trace-rb/pull/1936 . I've built the packages locally without releasing them, and validated that libddprof integration tests in the mentioned PR are all passing. 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Allow sending tags when building the HTTP request. Deduplicate tags and
prefer earlier tags from later tags.

Potentially, add FFI API for building tags dynamically.

# Motivation

For some clients, sending tags when the HTTP request is built is a more
natural place to do it than when the exporter is created. For others,
there are both static and dynamic tags and it's nice to have two places
to add tags so that you aren't forced to combine them.

Overall, I think it's much nicer this way.

This also includes an FFI API to build a `Vec<Tag>`. I need something
like this for PHP, and if any other languages need it then I think we
should put this into the API. If not, PHP can Just Deal With It.

# Additional Notes

Tag deduplication is not tested, not even manually yet.

I have tried the Vec API out from C in the PHP profiler, so on the
surface level it looks okay. If others want this, then there should be
tests.

# How to test the change?

Describe here in detail how the change can be validated.

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Allow sending tags when building the HTTP request. Deduplicate tags and
prefer earlier tags from later tags.

Potentially, add FFI API for building tags dynamically.

# Motivation

For some clients, sending tags when the HTTP request is built is a more
natural place to do it than when the exporter is created. For others,
there are both static and dynamic tags and it's nice to have two places
to add tags so that you aren't forced to combine them.

Overall, I think it's much nicer this way.

This also includes an FFI API to build a `Vec<Tag>`. I need something
like this for PHP, and if any other languages need it then I think we
should put this into the API. If not, PHP can Just Deal With It.

# Additional Notes

Tag deduplication is not tested, not even manually yet.

I have tried the Vec API out from C in the PHP profiler, so on the
surface level it looks okay. If others want this, then there should be
tests.

# How to test the change?

Describe here in detail how the change can be validated.

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/morrisonlevi/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# What does this PR do?

Allow sending tags when building the HTTP request. Deduplicate tags and
prefer earlier tags from later tags.

Potentially, add FFI API for building tags dynamically.

# Motivation

For some clients, sending tags when the HTTP request is built is a more
natural place to do it than when the exporter is created. For others,
there are both static and dynamic tags and it's nice to have two places
to add tags so that you aren't forced to combine them.

Overall, I think it's much nicer this way.

This also includes an FFI API to build a `Vec<Tag>`. I need something
like this for PHP, and if any other languages need it then I think we
should put this into the API. If not, PHP can Just Deal With It.

# Additional Notes

Tag deduplication is not tested, not even manually yet.

I have tried the Vec API out from C in the PHP profiler, so on the
surface level it looks okay. If others want this, then there should be
tests.

# How to test the change?

Describe here in detail how the change can be validated.

Allow sending tags when building the HTTP request. Deduplicate tags and
prefer earlier tags from later tags.

Potentially, add FFI API for building tags dynamically.

# Motivation

For some clients, sending tags when the HTTP request is built is a more
natural place to do it than when the exporter is created. For others,
there are both static and dynamic tags and it's nice to have two places
to add tags so that you aren't forced to combine them.

Overall, I think it's much nicer this way.

This also includes an FFI API to build a `Vec<Tag>`. I need something
like this for PHP, and if any other languages need it then I think we
should put this into the API. If not, PHP can Just Deal With It.

# Additional Notes

Tag deduplication is not tested, not even manually yet.

I have tried the Vec API out from C in the PHP profiler, so on the
surface level it looks okay. If others want this, then there should be
tests.

# How to test the change?

Describe here in detail how the change can be validated.

+# typed: ignore
+
+require 'datadog/appsec/spec_helper'
+require 'datadog/appsec/processor'
+
+RSpec.describe Datadog::AppSec::Processor do
+  before do
+    skip 'disabled for Java' if RUBY_PLATFORM.include?('java')
+
+    logger = double(Datadog::Core::Logger)
+    allow(logger).to receive(:debug?).and_return true
+    allow(logger).to receive(:debug)
+    allow(logger).to receive(:info)
+    allow(logger).to receive(:warn)
+    allow(logger).to receive(:error)
+
+    allow(Datadog).to receive(:logger).and_return(logger)
+  end
+
+  context 'self' do
+    it 'detects if the WAF is unavailable' do
+      hide_const('Datadog::AppSec::WAF')
+
+      expect(described_class.libddwaf_required?).to be false

{'action': 'created', 'comment': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/DataDog/dd-trace-rb/pulls/comments/837360676', 'pull_request_review_id': 924331145, 'id': 837360676, 'node_id': 'PRRC_kwDOA_arKM4x6Rwk', 'diff_hunk': "@@ -0,0 +1,227 @@
+# typed: ignore
+
+require 'datadog/appsec/spec_helper'
+require 'datadog/appsec/processor'
+
+RSpec.describe Datadog::AppSec::Processor do
+  before do
+    skip 'disabled for Java' if RUBY_PLATFORM.include?('java')
+
+    logger = double(Datadog::Core::Logger)
+    allow(logger).to receive(:debug?).and_return true
+    allow(logger).to receive(:debug)
+    allow(logger).to receive(:info)
+    allow(logger).to receive(:warn)
+    allow(logger).to receive(:error)
+
+    allow(Datadog).to receive(:logger).and_return(logger)
+  end
+
+  context 'self' do
+    it 'detects if the WAF is unavailable' do
+      hide_const('Datadog::AppSec::WAF')
+
+      expect(described_class.libddwaf_required?).to be false
+    end
+
+    it 'detects if the WAF is available' do
+      stub_const('Datadog::AppSec::WAF', Module.new)
+
+      expect(described_class.libddwaf_required?).to be true
+    end

+# typed: ignore
+
+require 'datadog/appsec/spec_helper'
+require 'datadog/appsec/processor'
+
+RSpec.describe Datadog::AppSec::Processor do
+  before do
+    skip 'disabled for Java' if RUBY_PLATFORM.include?('java')
+
+    logger = double(Datadog::Core::Logger)
+    allow(logger).to receive(:debug?).and_return true
+    allow(logger).to receive(:debug)
+    allow(logger).to receive(:info)
+    allow(logger).to receive(:warn)
+    allow(logger).to receive(:error)
+
+    allow(Datadog).to receive(:logger).and_return(logger)
+  end
+
+  context 'self' do
+    it 'detects if the WAF is unavailable' do

+# typed: ignore

+require 'datadog/appsec/assets'
+
+module Datadog
+  module AppSec
+    # Processor integrates libddwaf into datadog/appsec
+    class Processor
+      # Interface object to check using case .. when
+      module IOLike
+        def read; end
+        def rewind; end
+
+        def self.===(other)
+          instance_methods.reduce(true) { |ok, meth| ok && other.respond_to?(meth) }
+        end
+      end
+
+      def initialize
+        unless load_libddwaf && load_ruleset && create_waf_handle
+          Datadog.logger.warn { 'appsec is disabled, cause: errors' }
+        end
+      end
+
+      def ready?
+        !@ruleset.nil? && !@handle.nil?
+      end
+
+      def context
+        Datadog::AppSec::WAF::Context.new(@handle)
+      end
+
+      private
+
+      def load_libddwaf
+        Processor.require_libddwaf && Processor.libddwaf_required?
+      end
+
+      def load_ruleset
+        ruleset_setting = Datadog::AppSec.settings.ruleset
+
+        begin
+          @ruleset = case ruleset_setting

+                       JSON.parse(Datadog::AppSec::Assets.waf_rules(ruleset_setting))

+                       JSON.parse(File.read(ruleset_setting))
+                     when IOLike

+                     when Hash
+                       ruleset_setting
+                     else
+                       raise ArgumentError, "unsupported value for ruleset setting: #{ruleset_setting.inspect}"
+                     end
+

+          end
+
+          false
+        end
+      end

+  module AppSec
+    # Processor integrates libddwaf into datadog/appsec
+    class Processor
+      # Interface object to check using case .. when
+      module IOLike
+        def read; end
+        def rewind; end

+        def self.===(other)
+          instance_methods.reduce(true) { |ok, meth| ok && other.respond_to?(meth) }

+      end

+        unless load_libddwaf && load_ruleset && create_waf_handle

+      end

+# typed: ignore
+
+require 'datadog/appsec/assets'
+
+module Datadog
+  module AppSec
+    # Processor integrates libddwaf into datadog/appsec
+    class Processor
+      # Interface object to check using case .. when
+      module IOLike
+        def read; end
+        def rewind; end
+
+        def self.===(other)
+          instance_methods.reduce(true) { |ok, meth| ok && other.respond_to?(meth) }
+        end
+      end
+
+      def initialize
+        unless load_libddwaf && load_ruleset && create_waf_handle
+          Datadog.logger.warn { 'appsec is disabled, cause: errors' }
+        end
+      end
+
+      def ready?
+        !@ruleset.nil? && !@handle.nil?
+      end
+
+      def context
+        Datadog::AppSec::WAF::Context.new(@handle)
+      end
+
+      private
+
+      def load_libddwaf
+        Processor.require_libddwaf && Processor.libddwaf_required?
+      end
+
+      def load_ruleset
+        ruleset_setting = Datadog::AppSec.settings.ruleset
+
+        begin
+          @ruleset = case ruleset_setting
+                     when :recommended, :risky, :strict
+                       JSON.parse(Datadog::AppSec::Assets.waf_rules(ruleset_setting))
+                     when String
+                       JSON.parse(File.read(ruleset_setting))
+                     when IOLike
+                       JSON.parse(ruleset_setting.read).tap { ruleset_setting.rewind }
+                     when Hash
+                       ruleset_setting
+                     else
+                       raise ArgumentError, "unsupported value for ruleset setting: #{ruleset_setting.inspect}"
+                     end
+
+          true
+        rescue StandardError => e
+          Datadog.logger.error do

+module Datadog
+  module AppSec
+    # Processor integrates libddwaf into datadog/appsec
+    class Processor
+      # Interface object to check using case .. when
+      module IOLike
+        def read; end
+        def rewind; end
+
+        def self.===(other)
+          instance_methods.reduce(true) { |ok, meth| ok && other.respond_to?(meth) }
+        end
+      end
+
+      def initialize
+        unless load_libddwaf && load_ruleset && create_waf_handle
+          Datadog.logger.warn { 'appsec is disabled, cause: errors' }

+      end
+

+        !@ruleset.nil? && !@handle.nil?
+      end

+# typed: ignore

+module Datadog
+  module AppSec
+    # Processor integrates libddwaf into datadog/appsec
+    class Processor
+      # Interface object to check using case .. when
+      module IOLike
+        def read; end
+        def rewind; end
+
+        def self.===(other)
+          instance_methods.reduce(true) { |ok, meth| ok && other.respond_to?(meth) }
+        end
+      end
+
+      def initialize
+        unless load_libddwaf && load_ruleset && create_waf_handle
+          Datadog.logger.warn { 'appsec is disabled, cause: errors' }
+        end
+      end
+
+      def ready?
+        !@ruleset.nil? && !@handle.nil?
+      end
+
+      def context
+        Datadog::AppSec::WAF::Context.new(@handle)
+      end
+
+      private
+
+      def load_libddwaf
+        Processor.require_libddwaf && Processor.libddwaf_required?
+      end
+
+      def load_ruleset
+        ruleset_setting = Datadog::AppSec.settings.ruleset
+
+        begin
+          @ruleset = case ruleset_setting
+                     when :recommended, :risky, :strict
+                       JSON.parse(Datadog::AppSec::Assets.waf_rules(ruleset_setting))
+                     when String
+                       JSON.parse(File.read(ruleset_setting))
+                     when IOLike
+                       JSON.parse(ruleset_setting.read).tap { ruleset_setting.rewind }
+                     when Hash
+                       ruleset_setting
+                     else
+                       raise ArgumentError, "unsupported value for ruleset setting: #{ruleset_setting.inspect}"
+                     end
+
+          true
+        rescue StandardError => e
+          Datadog.logger.error do
+            "libddwaf ruleset failed to load, ruleset: #{ruleset_setting.inspect} error:#{e.inspect}"
+          end
+
+          false
+        end
+      end
+
+      def create_waf_handle
+        Datadog::AppSec::WAF.logger = Datadog.logger if Datadog.logger.debug? && Datadog::AppSec.settings.waf_debug
+        @handle = Datadog::AppSec::WAF::Handle.new(@ruleset)
+
+        true
+      rescue StandardError => e
+        Datadog.logger.error do
+          "libddwaf failed to initialize, error: #{e.inspect}"
+        end
+
+        false
+      end
+
+      class << self
+        def libddwaf_required?
+          defined?(Datadog::AppSec::WAF) ? true : false
+        end
+
+        def require_libddwaf

This PR prepares the 0.5.0 Ruby packages, and includes a bunch of changes to take advantage of 0.5 improvements:

* Exclude debug information from Ruby packages
* Package Linux arm64 releases for Ruby
* Changes the strategy for the fallback package with no platform (see more details in the change to the `Rakefile`)

(I've broken it into separate commits which hopefully will make sense individually)

# Motivation

Release latest improvements for usage by the Ruby profiler.

# Additional Notes

Using `docker-compose run push_to_rubygems` to release the packages won't work until we actually upload the 0.5.0-rc.1 binaries as 0.5.0. I built the packages locally and validated the dd-trace-rb tests are green (see "How to test the change?" below).

Also note that libddprof is not yet being used in any released version of dd-trace-rb, and more validation will be done on the Ruby side before we do so.

# How to test the change?

Libddprof integration is still in PR for dd-trace-rb. Testing can be done with https://github.com/DataDog/dd-trace-rb/pull/1936 . I've built the packages locally without releasing them, and validated that libddprof integration tests in the mentioned PR are all passing. {'push_id': 9446640138, 'size': 2, 'distinct_size': 2, 'ref': 'refs/heads/master', 'head': '710159bea121bb9ed832e98cad1909ef87d8810b', 'before': 'ba4b04a759e6c23e8129d6b61f49da793c984129', 'commits': [{'sha': '4b19c295a02802268256a4f842358838fb847ce3', 'author': {'email': 'ivo.anjo@datadoghq.com', 'name': 'Ivo Anjo'}, 'message': 'Remove CI resource class workaround due to grpc issue

While being installed, the grpc gem compiles a bunch of native code.

In #1791 I documented an issue we were running into in Circle CI where
the CI worker was running out of memory because grpc was spawning
too many parallel processes for compilation.

I brought the issue up with upstream in
https://github.com/grpc/grpc/issues/28244 and in
https://github.com/grpc/grpc/pull/28250 a new flag was added to
enable us to limit the number of processes used.

So now we can remove our workaround of bumping the resource class
put in place in #1790 and instead use the `GRPC_RUBY_BUILD_PROCS`
flag to tell grpc how many processes to use.

Fixes #1791', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/DataDog/dd-trace-rb/commits/4b19c295a02802268256a4f842358838fb847ce3'}, {'sha': '710159bea121bb9ed832e98cad1909ef87d8810b', 'author': {'email': 'ivo.anjo@datadoghq.com', 'name': 'Ivo Anjo'}, 'message': 'Merge pull request #1947 from DataDog/ivoanjo/remove-gprc-ci-resource-class-workaround

Remove CI resource class workaround for Ruby 3.1 due to grpc issue', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/DataDog/dd-trace-rb/commits/710159bea121bb9ed832e98cad1909ef87d8810b'}]}
